Former Baringo governor Benjamin Cheboi has edged closer to a comeback into county politics after he won the United Democratic Party (UDA) ticket on Friday. Cheboi garnered 45,666 votes to edge out incumbent governor Stanley Kiptis who came third with 25,976 votes in the hotly contested nominations. Eldama-Ravine Member of Parliament Moses Lessonet came second with 30,588 votes. "I thank God and most sincerely my people of Baringo for trusting and enabling me to win the UDA ticket" Cheboi said. Former Principal Secretary, State Department for Wildlife in the Ministry of Tourism and Wildlife,Â Fred Segor was fourth with with 16,362 votes while Robert Chelagat finished last with 6,056 votes. Cheboi now faces a tough hurdle ahead as he will now face Chama Cha Mashinani (CCM) flag bearer Richard Koech at the August 9 general election. It is now incumbent upon the people of Baringo to choose who between Cheboi and Koech shall be the next county Governor. Meanwhile, Baringo North MP William Cheptumo won the county senate UDA ticket after garnering 69, 420 votes while Isaiah Kirukmet came second with 25,681 votes. Tenges Ward MCA Silas Tochim came third with 13,633 votes while Bishop Jackson Kosgei got 7,515 votes. East Africa Legislative Assembly (EALA) MP Florence Jematia won the UDA ticket to vie for the Baringo Woman Rep post with 73,573 votes beating Susan Chesyna who came second with 33,757 votes. Nancy Chesire got 10,650 votes. Jematia now faces the incumbent Gladwel Cheruiyot who will be seeking to retain the seat on the Independent Kenya Africa National Union (KANU) party ticket.